<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06107251 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06107251 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Mandela  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  MURDER; TRIAL; SPOUSE; BLACK; POLITICS; LEADER; SOUTH-AFRICA  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Winnie Mandela testified today that she was hundreds of miles away on socialwork when four youths were allegedly abducted and beaten at her home inSoweto.;    Mandela, testifying for the first time in her kidnap and assaulttrial, said she was away from home for two days when the assault allegedlytook place. She said she met with large numbers of people in the town ofBrandfort during the time in question.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  MANDELA TAKES STAND AT HER MURDER TRIAL  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Mandela, dressed in a white suit, was largely expressionless as she gaveshort, flat answers to her lawyer during three hours of questioning.;   Mandela, Xoliswa Falati and John Morgan face eight counts of kidnapping andassault.;    Prosecutors charge the three abducted four black youths inDecember 1988 and beat them at Mandela's home. The state says the four wereabducted because it was believed they were homosexuals or police spies.;   Mandela, the wife of African National Congress leader Nelson Mandela, and herco-defendants pleaded not guilty. Mandela has said she tried to protect thefour young men from sexual abuse at a Methodist Church home where they livedbut knew nothing about an abduction or assaults.;    One of the four youngmen, Stompie Seipei, was later killed. Mandela's former bodyguard, JerryRichardson, was convicted last year of the killing.;    Mandela said Falaticame to her in December 1988 and said one of the boys at the church home hadbeen sexually abused by the white minister, Rev. Paul Verryn.;    Mandela saidshe was surprised because she had been told before of alleged homosexual abuseat the church home and had reported it to the church authorities. She saidFalati returned with the youth, who was about 13, and he was hysterical.;   &quot;He was very shocked. He found it difficult to speak to me,&quot; she said.;    Sheand Falati took the youth to a doctor, who said he had not been raped but wasin need of psychological attention. Mandela said she then left for Brandfortfor two days to help in community social work.;    Chief defense lawyer GeorgeBizos told the court he would call witnesses to show Mandela did not take partin any crime. He also said he would call witnesses to show there washomosexual abuse at the church home that figures in the case.;    &quot;No one wasassaulted by her or in her presence,&quot; he said of Mandela.;    Bizos also saidhe would subpoena various journalists about articles they wrote on the case.The journalists involved have indicated they are not prepared to revealconfidential sources.;    Mandela testified about her background and politicalwork. She spoke about her marriage to Nelson Mandela and about beingprosecuted for anti-apartheid work.;    She also said rooms at the back of herhome in the black township of Soweto were used by youths who were homeless orfleeing from the police for political reasons. The four alleged victims stayedin the rooms.;    &quot;My place was some kind of refuge,&quot; she said.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Johannesburg, South Africa  </CITY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910416  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  April  </MONTH><PG.COL>  8A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  499  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday April 16, 199100107251,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>